{{Infobox company | name = Eymundsson | image = [[Image:Eymundsson Austurstræti by Olafur Thorisson.jpg|300px|Eymundsson, book store, located on Austurstæti in downtown Reykjavik.]] | type = Retail | foundation = 29 november, 1872 | founder = Sigfús Eymundsson | location_city = [[Reykjavík]] | location_country = [[Iceland]] | products = books, magazines, stationary, gift items, DVDs, CDs. | homepage = {{URL|www.eymundsson.is}} }}
'''Eymundsson''' is [[Iceland]]'s oldest bookstore, established in 1872.<ref name="eymundsson">{{cite web|url=http://www.eymundsson.is|title=Eymundsson - Bóksali frá 1872|publisher=eymundsson.is|accessdate=8 August 2014}}</ref><ref name="timarit">{{cite web|url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?issId=361026&pageId=5805904&lang=is&q=Eymundsson%201872%20Eymundsson%20Eymundsson|title=Fréttatíminn, 2. árgangur 2011, 46. tölublað - Timarit.is|publisher=timarit.is|accessdate=8 August 2014}}</ref><ref name="timarit2">{{cite web|url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?issId=130106&pageId=1893575&lang=is&q=1872%20Eymundsson|title=Morgunblaðið, 07.12.1997 - Timarit.is|publisher=timarit.is|accessdate=8 August 2014}}</ref> It operates 15 locations around Iceland and offers a wide selection of books, magazines and various gift items. Many of their storefronts also include a coffeehouse. The store offers Iceland’s largest selection of foreign books and Icelandic literature in English.<ref name="globalblue">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalblue.com/destinations/iceland/reykjavik/read-between-the-lines-at-eymundsson/|title=Read between the lines at Eymundsson &#124; Global Blue|publisher=globalblue.com|accessdate=8 August 2014}}</ref>
== History == [[Sigfús Eymundsson]], a photographer and a [[Bookbinding|bookbinder]] founded "Bókaverslun Sigfúsar Eymundsson"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timarit.is/view_page_init.jsp?pageId=2290544|title=Sigfús Eymundsson bóksali|date=March 1907|work=Oðin|page=1|accessdate=7 August 2014|language=Icelandic}}</ref> in 1872. In 1886 Sigfus founded Eymundsson [[publishing]] and in coming years he would publish many of Iceland's poets, including [[Hannes Hafstein]] and [[Bólu-Hjálmar]]. Sigfus was the first to import [[typewriter]]s and [[Safe|money safes]]. He was also the first Icelander to publish and sell [[postcard]]s, using his own photos as material.
In 1920 Eymundsson bought the house on Austurstræti 18. Today Eymundsson's store still stands on this spot, in house built in 1960.<ref name="eymundsson2">{{cite web|url=http://www.eymundsson.is/eymundsson/saga-eymundsson/|title=Saga Eymundsson&nbsp;&lt; Um Eymundsson &#124; Eymundsson|publisher=eymundsson.is|accessdate=8 August 2014}}</ref>
