Historically, women have sometimes been arrested or charged with public indecency, disturbing the peace, or lewd behavior for baring their breasts in public, even in jurisdictions where there was no law explicitly prohibiting doing so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/health/the-weird-wild-legal-history-of-breasts-and-104942336487.html |title=The Weird, Wild Legal History of Breasts and Nipples |website=[[Yahoo Health]] |date=12 December 2014 |accessdate=2015-01-20}}</ref> In [[New York state]], female toplessness was made legal around 1990, and when a woman was arrested there in 2005 for appearing topless in public, a court ruled in her favor and she later received US$29,000 in damages.<ref>NBC News. [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/19293933/ns/us_news-weird_news/t/nyc-pays-over-topless-arrest/#.VPOO4GTF938 "NYC pays $29,000 over topless arrest"] ''[[Associated Press]]'', New York, 18 June 2007. Retrieved on 1 March 2015.</ref>

In 2015, the campaign received attention in [[Iceland]] after a teenage student activist posted a photo of herself topless and was harassed for doing so. In support of the student and the initiative, [[Björt Ólafsdóttir]], a [[Parliament of Iceland|Member of Parliament]], posted a topless photo of herself in solidarity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/apr/06/free-the-nipple-liberation-photos-breasts |title=#FreeTheNipple: liberation or titillation? |first=Sophie |last=Heawood |publisher=The Guardian |date=6 April 2015 |accessdate=2015-12-22}}</ref>

