* {{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/boots-free-the-nipple-photos-nudity-policy-breasts-march-develop-film-bee-a7910891.html|title=Boots 'refused' to print photographs from 'Free the Nipple' march|date=24 August 2017|publisher=}}
* {{cite web|url=http://www.alamy.com/stock-photo-brighton-uk-19th-aug-2017-free-the-nipple-protest-in-brighton-credit-154652418.html|title=Stock Photo - Brighton, UK. 19th Aug, 2017. Free the Nipple Protest|first=Rupert |last=Rivett|website=Alamy}}
* {{cite web|url=http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/15484543.Campaigners_march_along_Brighton_seafront_to__free_the_nipple |title=Campaigners march along Brighton seafront to 'free the nipple'|website=The Argus}}</ref><ref name="facebook.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/freethenipbrighton/|title=freethenipbrighton|website=facebook.com}}</ref>

In 2017, a Free The Nipple event was held in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]], England, on the day also celebrated as [[Women's Equality Day]] and [[Go Topless Day]], on the anniversary of when [[Nineteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|women gained the right to vote in the United States in 1920]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/hull-east-yorkshire-news/women-take-tops-hulls-first-386257|title=Why these women went topless on Hessle Foreshore today|first=Elizabeth|last=Mackley|date=26 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref>

== Court cases ==
Various court cases in the United States have involved the question of whether women may publicly expose female breasts. Two examples are Erie v. Pap's A. M.,<ref>[https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=2550942384996791158&q=public+nudity&hl=en&as_sdt=2003 Erie v. Pap's A. M.]</ref>, and Barnes v. Glen Theatre.<ref>[https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=13977097322948440019&q=public+nudity&hl=en&as_sdt=2003 Barnes v. Glen Theatre]</ref> These involved ordinances that placed restrictions on how women were legally permitted to appear in public, focusing on banning any public exposure of the female breasts. A lawsuit was filed as Free the Nipple v. City of Fort Collins,<ref>[https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=10601192275792345743&q=people+v+santorelli&hl=en&as_sdt=2003 Free the Nipple v. City of Fort Collins]</ref> which was an attempt to remove the provision in the municipal code of [[Fort Collins, Colorado]], that prohibits women from revealing their breasts. An injunction prohibiting Fort Collins from enforcing the prohibition is currently in place.<ref>{{cite court
|litigants = Free the Nipple v. City of Fort Collins
|opinion=R. Brooke Jackson
|court=United States District Court, D. Colorado
|date = February 22, 2017
|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=10143827673979443731&hl=en&as_sdt=6,50
|access-date = March 26, 2018}}</ref>. The city of Fort Collins has appealed the injunction, but it remains in effect.

In total, there are three U.S. states where the mere showing of women's breasts is illegal: Indiana<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chicagoinc/ct-met-topless-law-1112-chicago-inc-20171110-story.html |title=Chicago's ban on uncovered women's breasts upheld by divided court |date= November 10, 2017 |publisher= Chicago Tribune |accessdate=2017-11-27}}</ref>, Tennessee, and Utah.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Fourteen states and many other cities have laws with ambiguous implications on how much a woman is allowed to expose her body.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}

== Social media campaign ==
Every social media platform has their own guideline and policy in regards to nudity and revealing nipples. Facebook only allows photos of nipples to be posted when it is "in the context of breastfeeding, birth giving and after-birth moments, health (for example, post-mastectomy, breast cancer awareness, or gender confirmation surgery), or an act of protest."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/communitystandards/objectionable_content/adult_nudity_sexual_activity/|title=Community Standards {{!}} Facebook|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-20}}</ref>  Instagram's guideline for nudity states "We know that there are times when people might want to share nude images that are artistic or creative in nature, but for a variety of reasons, we don't allow nudity on Instagram. This includes photos, videos, and some digitally-created content that show sexual intercourse, genitals, and close-ups of fully-nude buttocks. It also includes some photos of female nipples, but photos of post-mastectomy scarring and women actively breastfeeding are allowed. Nudity in photos of paintings and sculptures is OK, too."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://help.instagram.com/477434105621119|title=Community Guidelines – Instagram Help Center|website=Instagram}}</ref> Pinterest allows artistic and non-sexualized nudity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://help.pinterest.com/en/articles/nudity|title=Nudity|publisher=help.pinterest.com}}</ref> Their reasoning on why they allow nudity and mature content is for "art, safe sex education or advocacy for political protests". Instagram's CEO Kevin Systrom said that because of the Apple's App Store regulations, every app needs an age rating, if an app contains nudity, it has to be rated 17+, the CEO would prefer Instagram remain at its current rating of 12+, to attract a younger audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konbini.com/us/lifestyle/heres-real-reason-instagram-wont-freethenipple/|title=Here's the real reason Instagram won't #FreeTheNipple|first=Lydia|last=Morrish|date=5 October 2015|publisher=}}</ref> YouTube's policy allows nipples to be shown in content, however, will not allow sexually explicit material in content in which a woman's nipples are exposed. Google+ does not allow nipples to be shown unless they are cartoons. [[Flickr]] and [[Tumblr]] allow users to control how much nudity they want to see, but when the control settings are off then everything is allowed. Twitter allows everything to be shown when it comes to female nudity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hyperallergic.com/131620/your-concise-guide-to-social-medias-female-nipple-policies/|title=Your Concise Guide to Social Media's Female Nipple Policies|date=20 June 2014|publisher=}}</ref>

A tactic that activists have taken up is the use of the [[hashtag]] #FreeTheNipple. This tag has been used on Facebook, Instagram and Twitter, where it can be used for searching the databases for posts with the same tag.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.cogitatiopress.com/mediaandcommunication/article/download/989/989 |title=Raging Against the Machine: Network Gatekeeping and Collective Action on Social Media Platforms |first=Sarah Myers| last=West |publisher=Cogitatio |location=Lisbon |work=Media and Communication |volume=5 |issue=3 |pages=28–36 |issn=2183-2439 |doi=10.17645/mac.v5i3.989 |date=22 September 2017 |accessdate=2017-11-15}}</ref>

Some celebrities have expressed support for the #FreeTheNipple movement on social media, including [[Miley Cyrus]],<ref name="time.com">{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3631924/free-the-nipple-breasts-sex-symbol/|title=Free the Nipple! The Problem With How We Think About Breasts|website=Time}}</ref> [[Lena Dunham]],<ref name="time.com"/> [[Jennifer Aniston]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vogue.com/article/jennifer-aniston-justin-theroux-aveeno-beauty-wellness-friends-hair-reese-witherspoon|title=Jennifer Aniston on Bringing the #FreeTheNipple Movement to the Masses First|publisher=}}</ref> [[Scout Willis]],<ref name=ViceControversy>{{cite web |url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/wj5q3b/the-nipple-controversy|first=Tish|last=Weinstock|accessdate=2017-11-17 |date=4 June 2014 |website=[[Vice Media|Vice]] |title=The nipple controversy}}</ref> [[Rihanna]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allure.com/gallery/celebrities-free-the-nipple|title=18 Times Celebrities Freed the Nipple (NSFW)|first=Rosemary|last=Donahue|publisher=}}</ref> [[Cara Delevingne]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fashionista.com/2014/07/cara-delevingne-topless-free-the-nipple|title=Cara Delevingne Takes "Free the Nipple" Campaign to the Next Level|publisher=}}</ref> [[Emily Ratajkowski]], [[Naomi Campbell]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/9/16/9341015/free-the-nipple-naomi-campbell|title=Naomi Campbell's #FreeTheNipple photo couldn't survive Instagram's silly nudity rules|publisher=}}</ref>and [[Willow Smith]]. [[Miley Cyrus]] said, "The nipple, what you can't show, is what everyone has. But the jug part that everybody doesn't, you're allowed to show underboob. I've never understood the way it works" on [[Jimmy Kimmel Live]] where she spoke about the campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mic.com/articles/124497/miley-cyrus-made-a-brilliant-point-about-why-we-must-free-the-nipple|title=Believe It or Not, Miley Just Made a Brilliant Point About #FreeTheNipple|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.papermag.com/miley-cyrus-free-the-nipple-instagram-chrissy-teigen-rihanna-scout-wil-1810518754.html|title=Miley Cyrus Showed Her Nipples Off On Instagram Without Being Reported|date=20 May 2016|publisher=}}</ref>

== Film and television ==
In 2014, director Lina Esco released her American feature film ''[[Free the Nipple (film)|Free the Nipple]]''. The film is centered around a group of young women who take to the streets of New York City as they protest the legal and cultural taboos regarding female breasts by way of publicity stunts, graffiti installations, and [[First Amendment]] lawyers. After shooting the film in 2012, Esco found it difficult to get the film widely released, motivating her to start the campaign in December 2013.<ref>Esco, Lina. ''[[Free the Nipple (film)|Free the Nipple]]''. ''Disruptive Films Inc.'', 2014. Retrieved on 20 January 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/news/154681_the_naked_truth_behind_the_free_the_nipple_movement/ |title=The Naked Truth Behind the 'Free the Nipple' Movement |publisher=Etonline.com |date=3 December 2014 |accessdate=2015-04-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/free-nipple-picked-up-by-736179|title='Free The Nipple' Picked Up By Sundance Selects For North American Release|publisher=Hollywood Reporter|first=Austin|last=Siegemund-Broka|date=29 September 2014|accessdate=2015-12-21}}</ref>

In episode 106 of ''[[The Bold Type]]'', the main character, Kat, participates in the campaign on social media by going against Instagram's guidelines by posting pictures with male nipples pasted onto women's bodies. The character said that freeing the nipple is more than just about Instagram and more about equality.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.refinery29.com/2017/08/167301/bold-type-free-the-nipple-episode-6-instagram |first=Ariana |last=Romero |title=''The Bold Type'' Proves Freeing the Nipple is About So Much More than Instagram |date=9 August 2017 |website=[[Refinery29]]}}</ref>

