'''Margunn Bjørnholt''' (born 9 October 1958 in [[Bø, Telemark]]) is a Norwegian [[sociologist]] and [[economics|economist]]. She is a [[Academic ranks in Norway#Research professor|Research Professor]] at the [[Norwegian Centre for Violence and Traumatic Stress Studies]] (NKVTS). Her current research focuses primarily on [[gender-based violence]], work, family and [[gender equality]], [[Men's studies|men and masculinities]], and [[Human migration|migration]]. Other research fields include [[financial institution]]s, [[management]] and [[Organizational studies|organization]], [[feminist economics]], and [[cultural sociology]]. She is a former President of the [[Norwegian Association for Women's Rights]] and the [[Norwegian Women's Lobby]].

==Background and career==

She studied [[politics]], [[contemporary history]], [[regional planning]] and [[economics]], and holds a [[cand.mag.]] degree from the [[University of Tromsø]] (1981), an MA in [[international economics|European economic studies]] from the [[College of Europe]] in [[Bruges]] (1981–1982),<ref>[[Dieter Mahncke]], [[Léonce Bekemans]], [[Robert Picht]], eds. (1999). ''The College of Europe. Fifty Years of Service to Europe'', [[College of Europe]], Bruges, {{ISBN|9080498319}}</ref> a [[Magister (degree)#Denmark and Norway|mag.art.]] (PhD equivalent) in [[economic sociology]] from the [[University of Oslo]] (1995), with a dissertation on [[microfinance]], [[ethical banking|ethical]] and [[interest]]-free [[banking]], a fil.dr. (PhD) in [[gender studies]] from [[Örebro University]] (2014), with the dissertation ''Modern Men'' on men's [[Work–life balance|work–family arrangements]], intergenerational transmission and [[social change]],<ref>[http://bibsys-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/primo_library/libweb/action/dlDisplay.do?docId=BIBSYS_ILS143481010&vid=BIBSYS Modern men: A Norwegian 30-year longitudinal study of intergenerational transmission and social change], Oria.no</ref><ref name="policy-bio">{{cite web |url= http://www.policy.no/people/margunn-bjornholt |title= Margunn Bjørnholt |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Policy and Social Research |accessdate=22 November 2012}}</ref> and full professor competence in gender studies (2015).<ref name="policy-bio"/>

She has previously worked at the [[Regional Development Fund]] (now [[Innovation Norway]]), at the [[National Institute of Technology (Norway)|National Institute of Technology]], and as a partner in a consultancy, promoting [[regional development]] and [[entrepreneurship]], with a particular emphasis on [[female entrepreneur]]ship. From 1993 she was affiliated with the Project for an Alternative Future, a research project at what is now the [[Centre for Development and the Environment]] at the [[University of Oslo]]. Since 1997 she has worked as a researcher at [[Telemark Research Institute]], the [[Work Research Institute]] and the [[Department of Sociology and Human Geography, University of Oslo|Department of Sociology and Human Geography]] at the [[University of Oslo]]. She is now a [[Academic ranks in Norway#Research professor|Research Professor]] at the [[Norwegian Centre for Violence and Traumatic Stress Studies]] (NKVTS).<ref name="NKVTS">{{cite web |url= https://www.nkvts.no/ansatt/bjornholt-margunn/ |title= Bjørnholt, Margunn |author= |date= |work= |publisher=[[Norwegian Centre for Violence and Traumatic Stress Studies]] |accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>

She has been a [[visiting scholar]] at the [[Feminism and Legal Theory Project]] at [[Emory University School of Law]]<ref>{{cite web |url= http://web.gs.emory.edu/vulnerability/Affiliated%20Faculty/bjornholt.html |title= Margunn Bjørnholt |author= |date= |work= |publisher=[[Emory University]] |accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref> and at the [[GEXcel International Collegium for Advanced Transdisciplinary Gender Studies|GEXcel Center of Gender Excellence]], and has served as a national expert on gender equality to the [[European Commission]] [[Directorate-General for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities (European Commission)|DG for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities]].<ref name="policy-bio" />

==Research==
Her research interests encompass [[ethical banking]] and [[microfinance]], [[Organizational studies|organisational]] and [[Spatial analysis|spatial]] flexibility in the [[public sector]], [[management]], [[gender equality]], [[Work–life balance|work–family arrangements]], [[qualitative research]] methods and [[cultural sociology]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kilden.forskningsradet.no/c17223/ekspert/vis.html?tid=88115 |title=Margunn Bjørnholt |author= |date= |work=Expert database for gender research |publisher=[[Research Council of Norway]] |accessdate=4 October 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006164100/http://kilden.forskningsradet.no/c17223/ekspert/vis.html?tid=88115 |archivedate=6 October 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> She is an expert on men's role and agency in social change towards more egalitarian work–family arrangements.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ingenere.it/persone/bj-rnholt |title= Margunn Bjørnholt |author= |date= |work= |publisher=inGenere.it |accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref><ref name="ref1">{{cite web |url= http://eng.kilden.forskningsradet.no/c52778/nyhet/vis.html?tid=73385 |title= A Successful Work-Life Balance |author=Anita Haslie |date= 14 September 2010 |work= |publisher=[[Research Council of Norway]] Information Centre for Gender Research in Norway |accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref><ref name="ref2">{{cite news |title= Week-On, Week-Off Parenting |author= [[Belinda Luscombe]] |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,2024208,00.html |newspaper=[[TIME Magazine]] |date= 18 October 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= A Crazy 40-Year-Old Experiment Suggests Work-Life Balance Is Possible |author= [[Belinda Luscombe]] |url=http://healthland.time.com/2010/09/22/a-crazy-40-year-old-experiment-suggests-work-life-balance-is-possible/ |newspaper=[[TIME|TIME Healthland]] |date= 22 September 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref><ref name="ref3">{{cite news|title=Vekker oppsikt internasjonalt |author=Johnny Gimmestad |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/jobb/article3838161.ece |newspaper=[[Aftenposten]] |date=3 October 2010 |accessdate=15 April 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006050126/http://www.aftenposten.no/jobb/article3838161.ece |archivedate=6 October 2010 |df= }}</ref><ref name="ref4">{{cite journal |author=Bosse Parbring |year=2011 |title= Delat föräldraskap, delad arbetstid |journal=NIKK magasin |volume=2011 |issue=1 |pages= |publisher=[[Nordic Gender Institute]] |doi= |pmid= |pmc= |url=http://www.nikk.no/Delat+föräldraskap,+delad+arbetstid.b7C_wljIXZ.ips |accessdate= 15 April 2012 }}</ref><ref name="ref5">{{cite journal |author=[[Linn Stalsberg]] |year=2011 |title= En krympet likestillingsdebatt |journal=Forskningsmagasinet Apollon |volume=2011 |issue=1 |pages= |publisher=[[University of Oslo]] |doi= |pmid= |pmc= |url=http://www.apollon.uio.no/artikler/2011/likestilling.html |accessdate= 15 April 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Likestilling er bra for kjærligheten |author= Linn Hanssen |url=http://www.dagbladet.no/tekstarkiv/artikkel.php?id=5001060056105 |newspaper=[[Dagbladet]] |date= 4 June 2006 |accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://kilden.forskningsradet.no/c16880/artikkel/vis.html?tid=37485 |title= Delte arbeid ute og hjemme |author= Beret Bråten |date= 29 November 2005 |work= |publisher=[[Research Council of Norway]] Information Centre for Gender Research in Norway |accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref>

In recent years her research has focused on fathers and sons, and she has carried out a follow-up study 30 years later of [[Erik Grønseth]]'s pioneering, experimental gender equality research from the 1970s, which studied gendered patterns of breadwinning and care.<ref name="ref1" /><ref name="ref2" /><ref name="ref3" /><ref name="ref4" /><ref name="ref5" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/jobb/Det-lonner-seg-for-far-a-stelle-hjemme-5344292.html |title= Det lønner seg for far å stelle hjemme |last1= Gimmestad |first1=Johnny |last2= |first2= |date= 5 September 2010 |work= |publisher=[[Aftenposten]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Tenk nytt om tidsklemma  |author= Ingeborg Moe |url= |newspaper=[[Dagbladet]] |date= 12 December 2005 | pages= 1, 16, 17}}</ref> Another focus is the cultural adaptations and transnational practices of Polish emigrants to Norway, and how migration leads to social change.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.policy.no/research/cross-national-polish-norwegian-project-on-work-life-balance |title= EFFECT: Cross-national Polish–Norwegian project on work–life balance |author= |date= |work= |publisher=Policy and Social Research |accessdate=22 February 2014}}</ref> She currently heads a research project on intimate partner violence with emphasis on gender, gender equality and power at [[NKVTS]], which is funded by the [[Ministry of Justice and Public Security]].<ref>[http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/Gir-50-millioner-til-forskning-pa-vold-i-nare-relasjoner-7633617.html Gir 50 millioner til forskning på vold i nære relasjoner], ''Aftenposten''</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cristin.no/app/projects/show.jsf?id=502936 |title= CRIStin Projects |author= |date= |work= |publisher=[[CRIStin]] |accessdate=25 February 2016}}</ref>

She was co-editor, with the Scottish economist [[Ailsa McKay]], of the 2014 book ''Counting on [[Marilyn Waring]]: New Advances in Feminist Economics''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.forskning.no/artikler/2014/mai/391278 |title= – Klart vi kan jobbe mindre |author= Kristin Marie Skaar |date= 24 May 2014 |work= |publisher=[[forskning.no]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-06-18/women-unaccounted-for-in-global-economy-proves-waring-influence.html |title= Women Unaccounted for in Global Economy Proves Waring Influence |last1= Langeland |first1=Terje |last2= |first2= |date= 18 June 2013 |work= |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg.com]]}}</ref> The book was described by [[Alison Preston]] as "a timely reminder of the politics and economics underpinning what, how and by whom activities are valued." According to ''[[Choice: Current Reviews for Academic Libraries|Choice]]'', the book explores "a wide range of issues—including the fundamental meaning of economic growth and activity to consumption, health care, mortality, unpaid household work, mothering, education, nutrition, equality, and sustainability" and reveals "the breadth, depth, and substance that can grow from innovative ideas and critical analysis."<ref>{{cite journal |last= Sullivan |first=T.E. |last2= |first2= |year=2014 |title= Review: Counting on Marilyn Waring: new advances in feminist economics |url= |journal=[[Choice: Current Reviews for Academic Libraries]] |publisher= |volume=52 |issue=3 |pages= 52-1517|doi= 10.5860/CHOICE.185300 }}</ref> [[Diane Elson]] argues that "despite many valiant efforts, women do not as yet really count in the conduct of economic policy. This book is an imaginative contribution to an ongoing struggle."<ref>{{cite journal |last= Elson |first=Diane |authorlink= Diane Elson |year= 2015 |title= Book Review: Counting on Marilyn Waring: new advances in feminist economics |url=http://www.palgrave-journals.com/fr/journal/v109/n1/full/fr201458a.html |journal= Feminist Review |publisher= |volume=109 |pages= e9–e11|doi= 10.1057/fr.2014.58 |accessdate=25 February 2015 |issue=1}}</ref>

==Civic and political activities==
She was involved in the [[ethical banking]] movement in the 1990s as chair of a working group attempting to start a bank in Norway modelled after [[JAK Members Bank]] in Sweden. She has been President of the [[Norwegian Association for Women's Rights]] (2013–2016),<ref name="aftenposten2014">{{cite news |title= Mannsforsker ny leder i Norsk Kvinnesaksforening |url=http://www.aftenposten.no/nyheter/iriks/Mannsforsker-ny-leder-i-Norsk-Kvinnesaksforening-7563258.html |newspaper=[[Aftenposten]] |location= |publisher= |date=2014-05-11 |accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Amal Aden tildelt Gina Krog-prisen |url=http://www.adressa.no/nyheter/innenriks/2016/05/21/Amal-Aden-tildelt-Gina-Krogh-prisen-12769416.ece |newspaper=[[Adresseavisen]] |location= |publisher= |date=2016-05-21 |accessdate= }}</ref> President of the [[Norwegian Women's Lobby]] (2014–2016),<ref>{{cite news |title= Norsk kvinnebevegelse slår seg sammen i ny lobby  |author= |url=http://www.kureren.no/artikler/41326 |newspaper=Kureren |date= 29 January 2014 |accessdate=4 October 2014}}</ref> and board member of the [[International Alliance of Women]] (2013–2016).<ref>[http://womenalliance.org/board Board], [[International Alliance of Women]]</ref> She was a journalist for the feminist radio station [[radiOrakel]] in the early 1980s, and she was a candidate for the [[Green Party (Norway)|Green Party]] in the [[Norwegian local elections, 2015|2015 elections]].<ref>[http://www.budstikka.no/nyheter/nyheter/han-topper-barums-gronne/s/2-2.310-1.8666945 Han topper Bærums grønne], ''Budstikka'', 26 November 2014</ref>

